"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Broadway playwright; McClure’s managing editor"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"\"Spread Eagle\" ran on Broadway","detail":"Brooks served in three WWI offensives before briefly attending the University of Poitiers in 1919 with American soldiers — part of an experiment foreshadowing the GI Bill. He became managing editor of McClure's and adapted stories for Fox Film. His son Hugh Torbert Brooks (1923-1945) was killed at the Battle of the Bulge while a Yale freshman who had enlisted in the 3rd Army. (Wikipedia on George S. Brooks; FindAGrave)","body":"George Sprague Brooks's 1927 Broadway play \"Spread Eagle\" starred Raymond Massey and was directed by George Abbott. The FCC banned it from radio. Long believed lost, it was rediscovered in the basement of the New York Public Library.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"arts","header":"The FCC banned it from radio","body":"Spread Eagle — Jed Harris producing, George Abbott directing, Raymond Massey on stage — was barred from broadcast, lost for decades, then found in a New York Public Library basement and revived by LA Theatre Works with Ed Asner. Brooks had written it nine years after surviving Chateau-Thierry."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His son fell in the Bulge","body":"Hugh Torbert Brooks was killed on January 2, 1945, in the Battle of the Bulge — the second world war claiming the son of a man who had come through the Meuse-Argonne in the first."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"George Sprague Brooks","first_name":"George","last_name":"Brooks","middle_name":"Sprague","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Managing editor","organization":"McClure’s"},{"role":"Screenwriter","organization":"Fox Film","st